[{"category":"section","location":"physical-theory/#Potential-field","page":"Physical theory","text":"The magnetic field is based on the Altschuler and Newkirk (1969) and Zhang et al. (2019) model, where a potential field is defined\n\nPhi(r ־¸ ֿ†)\n= R_odot\n  sum_ג„“=0^infty\n    sum_m=0^ג„“\n      P_ג„“^m(cos ־¸)\n      leftg_ג„“ m cos(mֿ†) + h_ג„“ m sin(m ֿ†)right\n      frac\n        displaystyleleft(fracR_odotrright)^ג„“+1 - left(fracR_odotR_ssright)^ג„“+1 left(fracrR_ssright)^ג„“\n      \n        displaystyle ג„“ + 1 + ג„“ left(fracR_odotR_ssright)^2ג„“+1\n      \n\nand the magnetic field,\n\nmathbfB(r ־¸ ֿ†) = B_r(r ־¸ ֿ†) hatmathbfr + B_־¸(r ־¸ ֿ†) hatboldsymbol־¸ + B_ֿ†(r ־¸ ֿ†) hatboldsymbolֿ†\n\nis the negative gradient of the potential field:\n\nmathbfB(r ־¸ ֿ†)\n= - gradPhi(r ־¸ ֿ†)\n= - pdvPhir hatmathbfr\n  - frac1r pdvPhi־¸ hatboldsymbol־¸\n  - frac1r sin ־¸ pdvPhiֿ† hatboldsymbolֿ†\n\nNote, here P_ג„“^m is the associated Legendre Polynomial under quasi-Schmidt normalization.\n\nFor notational convenience, we define the potential function as a product solution, where each function is defined as\n\nbeginalign*\nF_ג„“(r) = frac\n    displaystyle left(fracR_odotrright)^ג„“+1 - left(fracR_odotR_ssright)^ג„“+1 left(fracrR_ssright)^ג„“\n\n    displaystyle ג„“ + 1 + ג„“left(fracR_odotR_ssright)^2ג„“+1\n \nG_ג„“m(־¸) = P_ג„“^m(cos ־¸) 1ex\nH_ג„“m(ֿ†) = g_ג„“m cos(mֿ†) + h_ג„“ m sin(mֿ†)\nendalign*\n\nNote that F, G, and H all implicitly depend on ג„“ and m (only ג„“ in F's case).\n\nSo, the potential function is instead\n\nPhi(r ־¸ ֿ†) = R_odot sum_ג„“=0^infty F_ג„“(r) sum_m=0^ג„“ G_ג„“m(־¸) H_ג„“m(ֿ†)","title":"Potential field"},{"category":"section","location":"physical-theory/#Derivatives-of-potential-field","page":"Physical theory","text":"We need the first and second derivatives of each single-variable function for use in the Jacobian of the magnetic field.\n\nbeginalign*\ndvr F_ג„“(r)\n= frac displaystyle\n  -(ג„“+1) fracR_odot^ג„“+1r^ג„“+2 - ג„“ left(fracR_odotR_ssright)^ג„“+1 fracr^ג„“-1R_ss^ג„“\n displaystyle\n  ג„“ + 1 + ג„“ left(fracR_odotR_ssright)^2ג„“+1\n 1ex\n= frac displaystyle\n  -fracג„“+1r left(fracR_odotrright)^ג„“+1 - fracג„“r left(fracR_odotR_ssright)^ג„“+1 left(fracrR_ssright)^ג„“\n displaystyle\n  ג„“ + 1 + ג„“ left(fracR_odotR_ssright)^2ג„“+1\n\n2ex\nfracd^2dr^2 F_ג„“(r)\n= fracdisplaystyle\n  (ג„“+1)(ג„“+2) fracR_odot^ג„“+1r^ג„“+3 - ג„“(ג„“-1) left(fracR_odotR_ssright)^ג„“+1 fracr^ג„“-2R_ss^ג„“\n displaystyle\n  ג„“ + 1 + ג„“ left(fracR_odotR_ssright)^2ג„“+1\n 1ex\n= fracdisplaystyle\n  frac(ג„“+1)(ג„“+2)r^2 left(fracR_odotrright)^ג„“+1 - fracג„“(ג„“-1)r^2 left(fracR_odotR_ssright)^ג„“+1 left(fracrR_ssright)^ג„“\n displaystyle\n  ג„“ + 1 + ג„“ left(fracR_odotR_ssright)^2ג„“+1\n\nendalign*\n\nbeginalign*\nfracdd־¸ G_ג„“m(־¸) = - sin(־¸)  fracdP_ג„“^m(cos־¸)d(cos־¸) 1ex\nfracd^2d־¸^2 G_ג„“m(־¸) = sin^2(־¸)  fracd^2 P_ג„“^m(cos־¸)d(cos־¸)^2 - cos(־¸)  fracdP_ג„“^m(cos־¸)d(cos־¸)\nendalign*\n\nbeginalign*\nfracddֿ† H_ג„“m(ֿ†) = m left-g_ג„“ m sin(mֿ†) + h_ג„“ m cos(mֿ†)right 1ex\nfracd^2dֿ†^2 H_ג„“m(ֿ†) = -m^2 g_ג„“ m cos(mֿ†) + h_ג„“ m sin(mֿ†) = -m^2 H_ג„“^m(ֿ†)\nendalign*","title":"Derivatives of potential field"},{"category":"section","location":"physical-theory/#Jacobian-of-magnetic-field","page":"Physical theory","text":"The Jacobian for an mathbbR^3 is a 3ֳ—3 matrix. For B, it is\n\nbeginalign*\nJmathbfB(r ־¸ ֿ†)\n= beginbmatrix\n    displaystyle -frac^2 Phi r^2                        \n    displaystyle -frac1rfrac^2 Phi ־¸   r \n    displaystyle -frac1r sin ־¸ frac^2 Phi ֿ†   r 05ex\n    displaystyle -frac1r frac^2 Phi r   ־¸ \n    displaystyle -frac1r^2 frac^2 Phi ־¸^2           \n    displaystyle -frac1r^2 sin־¸ frac^2 Phiֿ†  ־¸  05ex\n    displaystyle -frac1r sin ־¸ frac^2 Phi r   ֿ† \n    displaystyle -frac1r^2 sin ־¸ frac^2 Phi־¸  ֿ† \n    displaystyle -frac1r^2 sin^2־¸ frac^2 Phi ֿ†^2\nendbmatrix\n2ex\n= beginbmatrix\n    longleftarrow  grad^TT B_r  longrightarrow 05ex\n    longleftarrow  grad^TT B_־¸  longrightarrow 05ex\n    longleftarrow  grad^TT B_ֿ†  longrightarrow\nendbmatrix\nendalign*\n\nIn terms of the SHTC expansion, the Jacobian is\n\nJmathbfB(r ־¸ ֿ†)\n= R_odot sum_ג„“=0^infty sum_m = 0^ג„“ beginbmatrix\n    displaystyle -fracd^2F_ג„“dr^2 G_ג„“m H_ג„“m \n    displaystyle -frac1r dvF_ג„“r dvG_ג„“m־¸ H_ג„“m \n    displaystyle -frac1rsin־¸ dvF_ג„“r G_ג„“m dvH_ג„“mֿ† \n    2ex\n    displaystyle -frac1r dvF_ג„“r dvG_ג„“m־¸ H_ג„“m \n    displaystyle -frac1r^2 F_ג„“ fracd^2G_ג„“md־¸^2 H_ג„“m \n    displaystyle -frac1r^2sin־¸ F_ג„“ dvG_ג„“m־¸ dvH_ג„“mֿ† \n    2ex\n    displaystyle -frac1rsin־¸ dvF_ג„“r G_ג„“m dvH_ג„“mֿ† \n    displaystyle -frac1r^2sin־¸ F_ג„“ dvG_ג„“m־¸ dvH_ג„“mֿ† \n    displaystyle -frac1r^2sin^2־¸ F_ג„“ G_ג„“m fracd^2H_ג„“mdֿ†^2\nendbmatrix\n\nFactoring out the parts that appear in ־¦, we have\n\nJmathbfB(r ־¸ ֿ†)\n= sum_ג„“=0^infty sum_m = 0^ג„“ - R_odot F_ג„“(r) G_ג„“m(־¸) H_ג„“m(ֿ†) beginbmatrix\n    displaystyle frac1F_ג„“ fracd^2F_ג„“dr^2 \n    displaystyle frac1r frac1F_ג„“ G_ג„“m dvF_ג„“r dvG_ג„“m־¸ \n    displaystyle frac1rsin־¸ frac1F_ג„“ H_ג„“m dvF_ג„“r dvH_ג„“mֿ†\n    2ex\n    displaystyle frac1r frac1F_ג„“ G_ג„“m dvF_ג„“r dvG_ג„“m־¸ \n    displaystyle frac1r^2 frac1G_ג„“m fracd^2G_ג„“md־¸^2 \n    displaystyle frac1r^2sin־¸ frac1G_ג„“m H_ג„“m dvG_ג„“m־¸ dvH_ג„“mֿ†\n    2ex\n    displaystyle frac1r  sin־¸ frac1F_ג„“ H_ג„“m dvF_ג„“r dvH_ג„“mֿ† \n    displaystyle frac1r^2sin־¸ frac1G_ג„“m H_ג„“m dvG_ג„“m־¸ dvH_ג„“mֿ† \n    displaystyle frac1r^2sin^2־¸ frac1H_ג„“m fracd^2H_ג„“mdֿ†^2\nendbmatrix\n\nNote that since B is a gradient field, the Jacobian is symmetric (negative Hessian of ־¦).","title":"Jacobian of magnetic field"},{"category":"section","location":"physical-theory/#Gradient-of-the-field-strength","page":"Physical theory","text":"גˆ‡B = גˆ‡|B| can be determined from the Jacobian of B. What follows is a proof using index notation:\n\npdvBx_j\n= pdvx_j left(B_i B_iright)^12\n= frac12 left(B_i B_iright)^-12 left(2 B_i pdvB_ix_jright)\n= fracB_i pdvB_ix_jleft(B_k B_kright)^12\n= fracB_iB pdvB_ix_j\n\nwhich implies B = hatmathbfb  JmathbfB","title":"Gradient of the field strength"},{"category":"section","location":"physical-theory/#Desired-quantities","page":"Physical theory","text":"The following are the quantities we want to calculate\n\nThe potential field\n־¦ = sum_ג„“=0^infty sum_m=0^ג„“ R_odot F_ג„“(r) G_ג„“m(־¸) H_ג„“m(ֿ†) = sum_ג„“m Phi_ג„“^m\nwhere Phi_ג„“^m = R_odot F_ג„“(r) G_ג„“m(־¸) H_ג„“m(ֿ†)\nThe magnetic field\nmathbfB = - sum_ג„“m R_odot F_ג„“(r) G_ג„“m(־¸) H_ג„“m(ֿ†) left(frachatmathbfrF_ג„“ dvF_ג„“r + frachatboldsymbol־¸r G_ג„“m dvG_ג„“m־¸ + frachatboldsymbolֿ†r sin(־¸) H_ג„“m fracdH_ג„“mdvarphiright)\nThe magnetic field strength, B = |B|\nThe gradient of the magnetic field strength, גˆ‡B\nbeginalign*\ngrad B\n= grad sqrtB_r^2 + B_־¸^2 + B_ֿ†^2 1ex\n= frac1B beginbmatrix\n      longleftarrow  dpdvmathbfB^TTr                      longrightarrow \n      longleftarrow  dfrac1r dpdvmathbfB^TT־¸         longrightarrow \n      longleftarrow  dfrac1r sin ־¸ dpdvmathbfB^TTֿ†  longrightarrow\n  endbmatrix mathbfB\n1ex\n= frac1B beginbmatrix\n      uparrow    uparrow    uparrow  \n      grad B_r   grad B_־¸   grad B_ֿ† \n      downarrow  downarrow  downarrow\n  endbmatrix mathbfB 1ex\n= frac1B (JmathbfB)^TT mathbfB\nendalign*","title":"Desired quantities"},{"category":"section","location":"physical-theory/#References","page":"Physical theory","text":"Altschuler,ֲ M.ֲ D. and Newkirk,ֲ G. (1969). Magnetic fields and the structure of the solar corona: I: Methods of calculating coronal fields. Solarֲ Physics 9, 131ג€“149.\n\n\n\nZhang,ֲ M.; Zhao,ֲ L. and Rassoul,ֲ H.ֲ K. (2019). Stochastic Propagation of Solar Energetic Particles in Coronal and Interplanetary Magnetic Fields. Journalֲ ofֲ Physics:ֲ Conferenceֲ Series 1225, 012010.\n\n\n\n","title":"References"},{"category":"section","location":"#MagneticFieldSHTCExpander.jl","page":"Introduction","text":"Recreate magnetic field vectors out of spherical harmonic transform coefficients (SHTC).","title":"MagneticFieldSHTCExpander.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#API-Reference","page":"Introduction","text":"","title":"API Reference"},{"category":"function","location":"#MagneticFieldSHTCExpander.magneticfield","page":"Introduction","text":"magneticfield(r, ־¸, ֿ†, g, h) -> BField\n\nReturn the magnetic field at (r ־¸ ֿ†) as described by g_ג„“^m and h_ג„“^m.\n\nArguments\n\nr: radial distance form the origin (spherical coordinates)\n־¸: polar angle (ISO/physics spherical coordinates)\nֿ†: azimuthal angle (ISO/physics spherical coordinates)\ng, h: arrays (matrices) containing the spherical harmonic transform           coefficients (SHTC). g[ג„“,m] should yield g_ג„“^m and           h[ג„“,m] should yield h_ג„“^m\n\nSee also\n\ncollectmagneticfield\n\n\n\n\n\nmagneticfield(rvec, g, h)\n\nCall magneticfield using a Vector instead of specifying coordinates.\n\nrvec should be a 3-vector containing the (r ־¸ ֿ†) components.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"MagneticFieldSHTCExpander.magneticfield"},{"category":"function","location":"#MagneticFieldSHTCExpander.collectmagneticfield","page":"Introduction","text":"collectmagneticfield(rs, ־¸s, ֿ†s, g, h) -> Array{BField,3}\n\nEvaluate magneticfield for multiple position vectors. Returns a 3d array containing BField information, where each index corresponds to the index of the rs, ־¸s and ֿ†s vectors.\n\nArguments\n\nrs: vector of radial distances form the origin (spherical coordinates)\n־¸s: vector of polar angles (ISO/physics spherical coordinates)\nֿ†s: vector of azimuthal angles (ISO/physics spherical coordinates)\ng, h: arrays (matrices) containing the spherical harmonic transform           coefficients (SHTC). g[ג„“,m] should yield g_ג„“^m and           h[ג„“,m] should yield h_ג„“^m\n\nExamples\n\nbgrid = collectmagneticfield(rs, ־¸s, ֿ†s, g, h)\nr = rs[i]\n־¸ = ־¸s[j]\nֿ† = ֿ†s[k]\nmagneticfield(r, ־¸, ֿ†, g, h) == bgrid[i,j,k]\n\nSee also\n\nmagneticfield\n\n\n\n\n\nEssentially [magneticfield(r, ־¸, ֿ†) for ֿ† in ֿ†s]\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"MagneticFieldSHTCExpander.collectmagneticfield"},{"category":"type","location":"#MagneticFieldSHTCExpander.BField","page":"Introduction","text":"struct BField{PotType, FieldType, JacType}\n\nComposite data type containing information about the local magnetic field vector. Note that position information needed for magneticfield, (r ־¸ ֿ†) is not stored.\n\nFields\n\n־¦::Any: magnetic potential at (r ־¸ ֿ†)\nB::StaticArraysCore.SVector{3}: magnetic field at (r ־¸ ֿ†)\njacobianB::StaticArraysCore.SMatrix{3, 3, JacType, 9} where JacType: Jacobian matrix of magnetic field at (r ־¸ ֿ†)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"MagneticFieldSHTCExpander.BField"}]
